Nonlinear models

Author

Dr. Niloufar Abourashchi and Dr. Thomas Honnor

Introduction

We have seen models of the form: \[\begin{align*} Y=\beta_0+\beta_1X \end{align*}\] (Such models can be extended to include other covariates, but we are keeping things simple to start with.)

These can be considered to be linear models in two ways.

Firstly, they are linear in the covariates. That is, whatever the initial value of \(X\), if I increase \(X\) by \(1\) then there will be a constant and consistent increase in \(Y\) (of \(\beta_1\) for the equation above).

An example of a model which is nonlinear in the covariates is: \[\begin{align*} Y=\beta_0+\beta_1\times\log(X) \end{align*}\] We have seen models like this occurring before, when we have considered transformations of covariates.

Secondly, the original model above is linear in the coefficients. That is, whatever the initial value of \(\beta_1\), if I increase \(\beta_1\) by \(1\) then there will be a constant and consistent increase in \(Y\) (of \(X\) for the original equation above).

An example of a model which is nonlinear in the coefficients is: \[\begin{align*} Y=\beta_0+X^{\beta_1} \end{align*}\]

The discussion today focuses specifically on nonlinear models of the first form – models which are linear in the coefficients but nonlinear in the covariates. A general expression for such models is: \[\begin{align*} Y=\beta_0+\beta_1 f_1(X)+\beta_2 f_2(X)+...+\beta_p f_p(X) \end{align*}\]

There are a variety of choices for potential outcomes (\(Y\)) and covariates (\(X\)), but we decide here to focus on how an individual’s wage can be modelled using the individual’s age.

Wage %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=wage, x=age)) +
    geom_point()

Linear model

We might begin by fitting a linear regression model: \[\begin{align*} wage = \beta_0+\beta_1\times age \end{align*}\]

lm_1 <- lm(wage~age, data=Wage)
summary(lm_1)

plot(lm_1)

The numerical output indicates to us that every year a person ages, they are expected to increase their wage by \(\$707.28\). How reasonable does this seem from looking at the plot of the regression line and the diagnostic plots for the model?

The plot of the regression line appears to show the data in an “upside down u-shape” pattern. Rather than wage increasing linearly with age, it appears that wage increases with age up to a certain point, after which the relationship reverses and wage starts to decrease with age. The same pattern can be seen in the residuals vs fitted values plot.

The behaviour displayed by the data is not necessarily unexpected. As younger adults gain experience of the workplace they gain skills (and associated promotions) which generally lead them to earn more money. Age discrimination might limit the job opportunities available to older individuals, reducing their access to higher paying jobs, or older individuals may take on part time/casualised work as they have already built up sufficient savings or to work around potential health conditions.

Polynomial regression

An alternative possibility might be to build a nonlinear model for wage using polynomial functions of age. That is, build a model of the form: \[\begin{align*} wage = \beta_0+\beta_1\times age+\beta_2\times age^2+\beta_3\times age^3+...+\beta_p\times age^p \end{align*}\]

First order polynomial

The order of a polynomial is the maximum power to which the variable is raised. In that sense, the linear model considered above is exactly a first order polynomial model.

Second order polynomial

The “upside down u-shape” picture observed in the previous plots is similar to the shape formed by a quadratic relationship (powers of \(x\) up to \(2\)) with a negative second derivative (the coefficient \(\beta_2\) of \(x^2\) is negative). We can test such a model for this data.

lm_2 <- lm(wage~poly(age,2), data=Wage)
summary(lm_2)

The coefficient of \(age^2\), \(\beta_2\), is statistically significantly different from \(0\), indicating to us that the inclusion of \(age^2\) makes a valuable contribution to the model.

Likewise, the adjusted \(R^2\) for this model (\(0.08147\)) is greater than for the previous model (\(0.03795\)), supporting the inclusion of the \(age^2\) term.

Third order polynomial

If the second order polynomial model was an improvement over the linear model (a first order polynomial model), perhaps a third order polynomial model (aka a cubic model) is even better.

What do we note from this process?

The higher the order of the polynomial, the greater the flexibility in the model: \[\begin{align*} y=\beta_0+\beta_1x+\beta_2x^2+...+\beta_px^p \end{align*}\] A \(p^{th}\) order polynomial has \(p+1\) different coefficients.

That flexibility is represented visually by an increased number of “turning points”. The linear/first order polynomial model resulted in a straight line with no turning points. The quadratic/second order polynomial model resulted in an “upside down u-shaped” curve with one turning point. The cubic/third order polynomial model results in a curve with two turning points.

Higher order polynomials are more flexible, allowing us to model more complicated relationships. Given what we’re seen in previous sessions, it hopefully doesn’t come as a surprise that the additional flexibility will at some point become a detriment – we will be overfitting.

Twentieth order polynomial

We might progress on, up to something like a twentieth order polynomial model.

summary(lm_3)$adj.r.squared

lm_20 <- lm(wage~poly(age,20), data=Wage)

print(c(cv_20$cv,cv_20$se))
        CV         CV 
40.1488539  0.1297099

According to the adjusted \(R^2\) the twentieth order polynomial model is superior, while AIC and cross validation indicate that the third order polynomial model is superior. In such cases we can make arguments in favour of either of the two models, but might generally prefer to base our decision making on the cross validation results.

Where possible, it is always useful to plot the model.

age_grid <- seq(from=min(Wage$age),to=max(Wage$age),length.out=100)
age_grid_df <- tibble(age=age_grid)
age_grid_df$wage_predicted <- predict(lm_20,newdata=age_grid_df)

Wage %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=wage, x=age)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line(data=age_grid_df,
              mapping=aes(y=wage_predicted,x=age),
              color="red")

In doing so, we see some very wacky behaviour. This is not uncommon for polynomial models of higher degree.

The model is using the flexibility afforded to it to desperately fit even the observations at the extreme values of \(x\). We have come across one of the pitfalls of polynomial models: observations at every value of \(x\) have a direct impact on the coefficient estimates, and the coefficient values impact the prediction at every value of \(x\). This can result in scenarios where, in an attempt to fit well at lower values of \(x\), the model in turn produces very unusual results at higher values of \(x\), and vice versa.

Spline models

Polynomial models can suffer from the influence of every observation on the prediction at every value of \(x\). We might work around this by fitting different models to different ranges of \(x\).

Consider: \[\begin{align*} Y&=\beta_{0,1}+\beta_{1,1}X+\beta_{2,1}X^2+\beta_{3,1}X^3+...+\beta_{p,1}X^p & for\ X&<X^* \\ Y&=\beta_{0,2}+\beta_{1,2}X+\beta_{2,2}X^2+\beta_{3,2}X^3+...+\beta_{p,2}X^p & for\ X&\geq X^* \\ \end{align*}\]

The breakpoint between the models, \(X^*\), might then be referred to as a knot.

Naive spline

Consider fitting a cubic polynomial model on each side of a single knot, where the knot is chosen to be at the median of the data.

Wage_left <- Wage[Wage$age<median(Wage$age),]
Wage_right <- Wage[Wage$age>=median(Wage$age),]

lm_3_left <- lm(wage~poly(age,3),data=Wage_left)
lm_3_right <- lm(wage~poly(age,3),data=Wage_right)

age_grid_left <- seq(min(Wage$age),median(Wage$age),l=50)
age_grid_df_left <- tibble(age=age_grid_left)
age_grid_df_left$wage_predicted <- predict(lm_3_left,newdata=age_grid_df_left)

age_grid_right <- seq(median(Wage$age),max(Wage$age),l=50)
age_grid_df_right <- tibble(age=age_grid_right)
age_grid_df_right$wage_predicted <- predict(lm_3_right,newdata=age_grid_df_right)

age_grid_df <- rbind(age_grid_df_left,age_grid_df_right)

Wage %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=wage,x=age)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line(data=age_grid_df,
              mapping=aes(y=wage_predicted,x=age),
              color="red")

There are two downsides to this type of model.

The first is the likelihood of a discontinuity at the knot. It is very likely that at the knot, the value of the left polynomial is not identical to the value of the right polynomial. Not only are the values of the polynomials likely to differ at the knot, the values of the derivatives (rates of change) of the polynomials are likely to differ at the knot.

Ideally, we would like continuity (of the fitted model and its derivatives) at the knot. In such cases we would not see a jump in the value of wage at a particular value of age, nor would we see one relationship of wage with age on one side of the knot and a dramatically different relationship on the other side of the knot.

The second downside is a rapid increase in model complexity. The code above includes a single knot and third order polynomials, leading to eight different coefficients (that is, the model has eight degrees of freedom).

If we were to add another knot then we would add another four coefficients. If we were to increase the degree of our polynomial by one, we would add a number of coefficients equal to the number of knots plus one.

All together, \(k\) knots and polynomials of order \(p\) results in a total of \((p+1)\times(k+1)\) coefficients. Hopefully, this gives some insight that models like this one can quickly become highly flexible and in danger of overfitting.

Basis splines

One way to avoid the problems encountered by the naive spline model above is to enforce constraints on the fitted coefficients. For example: \[\begin{align*} Y&=\beta_{0,1}+\beta_{1,1}X+\beta_{2,1}X^2+\beta_{3,1}X^3 & for\ X&<X^* \\ Y&=\beta_{0,2}+\beta_{1,2}X+\beta_{2,2}X^2+\beta_{3,2}X^3 & for\ X&\geq X^* \\ \end{align*}\] with the restrictions that: \[\begin{align*} \beta_{0,1}+\beta_{1,1}X^* +\beta_{2,1}(X^*)^2 +\beta_{3,1}(X^*)^3 &= \beta_{0,2}+\beta_{1,2}X^* +\beta_{2,2}(X^*)^2 +\beta_{3,2}(X^*)^3 \\ \beta_{1,1} +2\times\beta_{2,1}X^* +3\times\beta_{3,1}(X^*)^2 &= \beta_{1,2} +2\times\beta_{2,2}X^* +3\times\beta_{3,2}(X^*)^2 \\ 2\times\beta_{2,1} +6\times\beta_{3,1}X^* &= 2\times\beta_{2,2} +6\times\beta_{3,2}X^* \end{align*}\]

Those three constraints enforce equality in the functions, their first derivatives and their second derivatives at the knot. That ensures a degree of smoothness at the knot, resolving one of the concerns of the previous naive model.

The presence of these constraints reduces the flexibility of the model. Specifically, the three constraints reduce the degrees of freedom by three, resulting in a model with \((4\times 2)-3=5\) degrees of freedom. Extending this logic, a model of this form using \(p\)-dimensional polynomials constrained to agree up to and including the \((p-1)^{th}\) derivative at \(k\) knots will have a total of \(p+1+k\) degrees of freedom. This is a dramatic reduction from the \((p+1)\times(k+1)\) degrees of freedom of the previous naive model.

Programming up a model like this is non-trivial. Fortunately, there are some mathematical optimisations which we won’t get into here through which the above model can be represented through a more straightforward combination of basis spline, or b-spline, functions.

library(splines)

It is possible to fit such models by specifying the knot locations.

fit_spline1 <- lm(wage~bs(age,knots=quantile(Wage$age,c(0.25,0.5,0.75))),data=Wage)

age_grid_df$wage <- predict(fit_spline1,newdata=age_grid_df)

ggplot(mapping=aes(y=wage,x=age)) +
  geom_point(data=Wage) +
  geom_line(data=age_grid_df,color="red")

Alternatively, it is possible to fit such models by specifying the desired degrees of freedom of the resulting model (the default is to use third order polynomials, but this can be modified via the degree argument to the bs function).

fit_spline2 <- lm(wage~bs(age,df=7),data=Wage)

age_grid_df$wage <- predict(fit_spline2,newdata=age_grid_df)

ggplot(mapping=aes(y=wage,x=age)) +
  geom_point(data=Wage) +
  geom_line(data=age_grid_df,color="red")

This model with degrees of freedom \(7\) is almost identical to the previous model with three knots, one at each of the lower quartile, median and upper quartile.

The somewhat local nature of the fitting process means that we may avoid the issues observed with higher order polynomial models. We previously considered a polynomial model of order \(20\), which has \(21\) degrees of freedom. Let us see how that compares to a spline model which also has \(21\) degrees of freedom.

fit_spline3 <- lm(wage~bs(age,df=21),data=Wage)

age_grid <- seq(from=min(Wage$age),to=max(Wage$age),length.out=100)
age_grid_df <- tibble(age=age_grid)

age_grid_df_poly <- age_grid_df
age_grid_df_poly$wage_predicted <- predict(lm_20,newdata=age_grid_df_poly)

age_grid_df_spline <- age_grid_df
age_grid_df_spline$wage_predicted <- predict(fit_spline3,newdata=age_grid_df_spline)

Wage %>%
  ggplot(aes(y=wage, x=age)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line(data=age_grid_df_spline,
              mapping=aes(y=wage_predicted,x=age),
              color="red") +
    geom_line(data=age_grid_df_poly,
              mapping=aes(y=wage_predicted,x=age),
              color="blue")

Optimising degrees of freedom

We now have at our disposal a family of models, parameterised by the number of degrees of freedom. As we have seen previously, a degrees of freedom which is too small may unnecessarily limit the flexibility of the model and cause us to underfit, whereas a degrees of freedom which is too large may include unnecessary flexibility and cause us to overfit.

Quantifying the accuracy of predictions for test data using models fitted to training data is one way to identify the sweet spot between underfitting and overfitting. Cross validation is one way to achieve this.

set.seed(2)

n <- nrow(Wage)

df_vals <- 4:25

n_vals <- length(df_vals)

results <- data.frame(df = rep(0,n_vals),
                      rmse_training = rep(0,n_vals),
                      rmse = rep(0,n_vals),
                      se = rep(0,n_vals))

for (i in 1:n_vals){
  
  df_i <- df_vals[i]
  
  fit_spline <- lm(wage~bs(age,df=df_i),data=Wage)
  
  cv_result <- cvFit(fit_spline, data = Wage,y = Wage$wage, K = 10, R = 10)
  
  results$df[i] <- df_i
  results$rmse[i] <- cv_result$cv
  results$se[i] <- cv_result$se
  
  wage_pred <- predict(fit_spline)
  rmse_train <- sqrt(sum((Wage$wage - wage_pred)^2)/n)
  results$rmse_training[i] <- rmse_train
  
}

print(results)

We may visualise how the error for the training and test datasets varies with the number of degrees of freedom.

ggplot(data=results) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=df, y=rmse)) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=df, y=rmse_training), color="red")

We may also visualise how the test error obtained via cross validation varies after incorporating the variability in the test error using different numbers of knots.

best_rmse <- min(results$rmse)
best_row <- which.min(results$rmse)
best_df <- results$df[best_row]
best_se <- results$se[best_row]

ggplot(data=results) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=df, y=rmse)) +
  geom_errorbar(mapping=aes(x=df, ymin=rmse-2*se, ymax=rmse+2*se)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = best_rmse, linetype="dashed") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = best_rmse+2*best_se, linetype="dotted") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = best_rmse-2*best_se, linetype="dotted")

To identify the best overall model, we first consider the model with the lowest cross validation error. In this case, that is the model with five degrees of freedom.

We then consider the uncertainty in that error. The error bars for the model with five degrees of freedom indicate that its performance is not statistically distinguishable from the models with four, six, seven, ten or eleven degrees of freedom.

We generally aim for parsimony – using the least complicated model we can get away with. As a result, we would make the decision to put forwards the model with four degrees of freedom as our best model in this case – it is the least complicated model which has error which is indistinguishable from the model with the very lowest error.

Local regression

Recall, splines were useful because the fitted function at some value of \(x\) was largely determined by other observations near \(x\) (those observations between the same two knots that \(x\) itself fell between), as opposed to by observations at all other values of \(x\). An alternative is a class of models referred to as local regression (shortened to loess or lowess depending upon the exact methodology followed).

It isn’t important for us to know the precise details of these methodologies, but more information can be found in Section 7.6 of the ISLR textbook. In short, they fit the model at a given value of \(x\) by minimising the weighted sum of squares of residuals in the neighbourhood of \(x\).

The weighting function applies full weight to values at \(x\), falling to zero as we move further away from \(x\). The rate at which the weight function decays is inversely related to what is called the span by the R function loess.

A large span means a slow decay in the weights, meaning that a wider range of observations contribute to the fit at \(x\), meaning that the fitted function is less flexible, and thus there may be the potential for underfitting. A small span means a fast decay in the weights, meaning that a narrower range of observations contribution to the fit at \(x\), meaning that the fitted function is more flexible, and thus that there may be the potential for overfitting. This flexibility can be summarised by an effective degrees of freedom measurement, and as you might expect cross validation may be tool to find an optimal span.

fit_loess1 <- loess(wage~age,span=.2,data=Wage)
fit_loess2 <- loess(wage~age,span=1,data=Wage)

Interpretability

One aim of model building is to make accurate predictions. In such cases, the interpretability of the model may be downplayed or ignored entirely.

In other cases, we might aim to gain some understanding of how \(x\) influences \(y\). In such cases, it might be nice to have a single equation summarising that relationship.

Consider the polynomial regression model, where there is one single equation which defines the predictions for every single value of \(x\). Next, consider the spline model, where there are \(k+1\) equations which define predictions, one equation for each between-knot range. Finally, consider the locally weighted regression model, where there is essentially a different equation at every unique value of \(x\).

Of course, it is natural to question whether the polynomial regression equation is itself actually all that interpretable. In the case of our degree twenty polynomial model it is impossible to make a simple statement along the lines of “as \(x\) increases by \(1\), \(y\) changes by \(z\)” because of the nonlinearity of polynomials of degree greater than one.
